HEADWORD: frailty
<hw>frail"ty</hw> <pr>(fr⟦amac⟧l"t⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>frailties</plw>
<pr>(fr⟦amac⟧l"t⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>frelete</ets>,
<ets>freilte</ets>, OF. <ets>frailet⟦eacute⟧</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>fragilitas</ets>. See <er>Frail</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Fragility</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The condition or quality of
being frail, physically, mentally, or morally; frailness; infirmity;
weakness of resolution; liableness to be deceived or seduced.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God knows our <qex>frailty</qex>, [and] pities our weakness.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fault proceeding from weakness; foible; sin of
infirmity.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Frailness; fragility; imperfection;
failing.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fraischeur</ent>⟦br⟧
